01:01:47.486 --> 01:01:49.978
agreement" to acquire the AMEX.]
I wanted to just finish with

01:01:49.978 --> 01:01:52.346
just a little bit of a thought
about what it means to be a

01:01:52.346 --> 01:01:56.610
dealer in this market.
What is it that if you are a

01:01:56.610 --> 01:02:03.032
dealer operating on one of these
exchanges, you are placing

01:02:03.032 --> 01:02:05.756
orders,
effectively,

01:02:05.756 --> 01:02:13.030
in somebody's book and standing
ready to buy or sell.

01:02:13.030 --> 01:02:18.302
A dealer is someone who is
trading everyday,

01:02:18.302 --> 01:02:23.820
who has an inventory of stocks
for trading.

01:02:23.820 --> 01:02:28.934
I want to just maybe close with
a little thought about what it's

01:02:28.934 --> 01:02:33.519
like to be a dealer.
I've never been a dealer and I

01:02:33.519 --> 01:02:39.024
don't know the emotional thing,
but the problem with being a

01:02:39.024 --> 01:02:44.809
dealer of any kind--maybe it
takes a certain moral stamina,

01:02:44.809 --> 01:02:47.238
mental stamina,
to do this kind of thing--is

01:02:47.238 --> 01:02:50.837
that you're trading everyday.
You're not someone who's

01:02:50.837 --> 01:02:55.074
managing the Yale portfolio.
What you're trying to do is

01:02:55.074 --> 01:02:59.305
make money everyday by buying
low and selling high and you

01:02:59.305 --> 01:03:03.908
have to be ready to stand--ready
to take orders--because people

01:03:03.908 --> 01:03:06.942
come to you.
Someone will come to you or

01:03:06.942 --> 01:03:10.685
there will be someone in a
specialist's crowd who wants to

01:03:10.685 --> 01:03:14.559
place an order or buy or sell
and you have an inventory.

01:03:14.559 --> 01:03:21.533
You're like an antiques dealer
and one problem is that your

01:03:21.533 --> 01:03:27.171
life's work, unfortunately,
as a dealer is summarized by

01:03:27.171 --> 01:03:29.860
your portfolio and your
inventory.

01:03:29.860 --> 01:03:32.579
That's why I didn't become a
dealer, actually.

01:03:32.579 --> 01:03:38.775
I don't--I guess you have to
have the right stomach of steel

01:03:38.775 --> 01:03:41.961
or something.
The thing that I wanted to

01:03:41.961 --> 01:03:45.059
impress on you is that no matter
how well you do,

01:03:45.059 --> 01:03:49.241
your cumulative score is there
in your portfolio and it's a

01:03:49.241 --> 01:03:53.355
competitive business.
So, you run the risk of being

01:03:53.355 --> 01:03:58.638
ruined at any time in your life.
This just--I want to remind you

01:03:58.638 --> 01:04:03.295
of what's called the gambler's
ruin problem because being a

01:04:03.295 --> 01:04:07.791
dealer is a little bit like
being someone who goes to the

01:04:07.791 --> 01:04:12.119
gambling casino everyday.
If you enjoy your visit to the

01:04:12.119 --> 01:04:15.190
gambling casino,
maybe you want to be a dealer.

01:04:15.190 --> 01:04:18.207
Actually, I don't really enjoy
it, so I'm just not the right

01:04:18.207 --> 01:04:20.967
person to do this.
What I really wouldn't like

01:04:20.967 --> 01:04:24.314
about it is that you always
stand the chance of being

01:04:24.314 --> 01:04:26.760
ruined--that is,
losing everything.

01:04:26.760 --> 01:04:29.845
So, I just want to review.
This is a little bit of

01:04:29.845 --> 01:04:33.800
mathematics that is in market
microstructure theory.

01:04:44.389 --> 01:04:49.017
Suppose you're a dealer and you
have a way of either winning or

01:04:49.017 --> 01:04:51.630
losing money on each
transaction.

01:04:51.630 --> 01:04:59.612
Suppose the probability of
winning on a transaction is

01:04:59.612 --> 01:05:08.800
equal to p--that's the
probability of winning on one of

01:05:08.800 --> 01:05:12.794
your trades.
To simplify this thing,

01:05:12.794 --> 01:05:15.480
let's say that you either win
or lose.

01:05:15.480 --> 01:05:24.860
If you win, you get $1;
if you lose, you lose $1.

01:05:24.860 --> 01:05:30.722
So, you win $1 with probability
p and you lose $1 with

01:05:30.722 --> 01:05:33.360
probability 1 - p.

01:05:38.849 --> 01:05:42.211
I want to know,
what is your life career going

01:05:42.211 --> 01:05:46.619
to look like if you're just
doing this everyday for the next

01:05:46.619 --> 01:05:50.973
thirty years?
Well, the first question is,

01:05:50.973 --> 01:05:56.039
what is the probability of your
being ruined?

01:05:56.039 --> 01:06:00.004
Let's start with the case
p = ½

01:06:00.004 --> 01:06:05.590
and let's not say--thirty years
is close enough to infinity,

01:06:05.590 --> 01:06:08.759
but let's just say you're going
to do this forever because I

01:06:08.759 --> 01:06:12.090
don't want to have to figure out
the effect of the last day.

01:06:12.090 --> 01:06:15.271
What do you think is the
probability of being--remember,

01:06:15.271 --> 01:06:18.510
being ruined means having your
inventory fall to zero.

01:06:18.510 --> 01:06:25.928
You start with S
dollars--that's capital S

01:06:25.928 --> 01:06:32.593
dollars--which is an integer.
When S falls to zero,

01:06:32.593 --> 01:06:35.850
you are "ruined;"
you don't have any money left;

01:06:35.850 --> 01:06:38.545
you're out of the game;
and you will be dismissed from

01:06:38.545 --> 01:06:40.879
the exchange.
If you can't trade anymore,

01:06:40.879 --> 01:06:43.638
you don't have anything.
You have to start with

01:06:43.638 --> 01:06:46.519
something, otherwise you can't
trade at all.

01:06:46.519 --> 01:06:48.949
So, S is something like
$100.

01:06:48.949 --> 01:06:51.809
If p as a point--do any
of you know the answer?

01:06:51.809 --> 01:06:55.680
What's the probability that I
will eventually be ruined?

01:07:01.280 --> 01:07:04.309
This isn't something that you
got in your probability theory?

01:07:04.309 --> 01:07:10.269
You got it right--that's right,
it's 100%.

01:07:10.269 --> 01:07:15.110
You will with certainty be
ruined.

01:07:15.110 --> 01:07:22.835
In fact, the probability of
ruin is ((1 -

01:07:22.835 --> 01:07:34.229
p)/p)^S,
if p is greater than .5

01:07:34.229 --> 01:07:41.791
or greater than-equal to .5.
That's because,

01:07:41.791 --> 01:07:45.292
if you substitute in .5,
this is 1, so,

01:07:45.292 --> 01:07:50.597
the probability of ruin is 1.
If it's--if the probability is

01:07:50.597 --> 01:07:54.056
greater than .5,
then the probability of ruin

01:07:54.056 --> 01:07:59.822
will be something less than 1.
This is actually easy to derive

01:07:59.822 --> 01:08:04.836
because--think of it this
way--we'll call this the

01:08:04.836 --> 01:08:10.260
probability of ruin,
if you have S dollars.

01:08:10.260 --> 01:08:17.985
The reason it has this is
because if I start with s

01:08:17.985 --> 01:08:22.864
dollars, there are two
possibilities:

01:08:22.864 --> 01:08:30.382
either gain $1 or lose $1.
So, this probability of

01:08:30.382 --> 01:08:39.237
S has to equal p x
Pr(S + 1) + (1 - p )

01:08:39.237 --> 01:08:43.439
x Pr(S â€“
1).

01:08:43.439 --> 01:08:48.216
That is the probability--this
is the probability of ruin if

01:08:48.216 --> 01:08:53.156
you have S + $1 and this
is the probability of ruin if

01:08:53.156 --> 01:08:57.131
you have S - $1.
So, the function determining

01:08:57.131 --> 01:09:00.510
probability of S has to
satisfy this equation.

01:09:00.510 --> 01:09:04.284
Also, we have the
restraint--the probability of

01:09:04.284 --> 01:09:09.043
ruin if you have zero dollars is
1, so this is a difference

01:09:09.043 --> 01:09:11.960
equation.
If you solve it, you get this.

01:09:11.960 --> 01:09:17.773
What it means is that you had
better have a probability of

01:09:17.773 --> 01:09:23.688
winning substantially above $1
or else have an awful lot of

01:09:23.688 --> 01:09:27.333
dollars to start with.
Unfortunately,

01:09:27.333 --> 01:09:30.808
it's hard to get the
probability of winning in any

01:09:30.808 --> 01:09:34.922
one trade much up above ½
because you're living in a

01:09:34.922 --> 01:09:39.886
competitive marketplace.
So, if p is close to

01:09:39.886 --> 01:09:45.159
½, it's just a little bit
above ½,

01:09:45.159 --> 01:09:48.209
then you will be standing for
your whole life,

01:09:48.209 --> 01:09:52.342
always with a probability that
the rest of my life is going to

01:09:52.342 --> 01:09:55.551
end up in ruin.
So, you may have been very

01:09:55.551 --> 01:09:58.729
successful and you now have
S = 1000,

01:09:58.729 --> 01:10:03.460
but the probability keeps going
down, but it never hits zero.

01:10:03.460 --> 01:10:07.680
Student: A gambler can
take money off the table.

01:10:07.680 --> 01:10:09.035
Professor Robert
Shiller: Well,

01:10:09.035 --> 01:10:10.720
that's what you have--that's
what people do.

01:10:10.720 --> 01:10:14.372
Student: I think you're
saying that the specialist--the

01:10:14.372 --> 01:10:16.369
first few [inaudible].
Professor Robert

01:10:16.369 --> 01:10:17.634
Shiller: Well,
they are taking money off

01:10:17.634 --> 01:10:18.869
the--maybe because they are
doing that.

01:10:18.869 --> 01:10:23.900
You live your life and you take
money off.

01:10:23.900 --> 01:10:29.096
Yeah, you're right;
I don't have to play it out to

01:10:29.096 --> 01:10:33.410
the bitter end like this.
I wanted to show--this is

01:10:33.410 --> 01:10:38.649
actually--this mathematical
model is something that you will

01:10:38.649 --> 01:10:43.711
find in the Page 1 or Chapter 1
of a market microstructure

01:10:43.711 --> 01:10:48.570
textbook because you're right;
there are strategies that can

01:10:48.570 --> 01:10:52.411
prevent ruin like that.
This is the basic--this is

01:10:52.411 --> 01:10:57.469
just--I'm presenting this as a
very simple model of what

01:10:57.469 --> 01:11:01.239
underlies the restriction on a
broker.

01:11:01.239 --> 01:11:06.228
A broker has to
maintain--create a strategy such

01:11:06.228 --> 01:11:11.853
that this p is
sufficiently probable--that this

01:11:11.853 --> 01:11:16.630
ruin problem doesn't become
catastrophic.

01:11:16.630 --> 01:11:20.539
The way they do that,
they set the bid-asked spread

01:11:20.539 --> 01:11:24.291
that a dealer has with
consideration of this ruin

01:11:24.291 --> 01:11:27.053
problem,
which has to be the focal point

01:11:27.053 --> 01:11:30.455
of their attention.
They have to set the bid-asked

01:11:30.455 --> 01:11:34.832
spread wide enough so that they
feel comfortable enough with

01:11:34.832 --> 01:11:38.927
this probability of ruin.
If you don't--of course,

01:11:38.927 --> 01:11:43.130
it's a competitive market and
so you can't get this

01:11:43.130 --> 01:11:48.078
probability up too high.
So, if you don't like this,

01:11:48.078 --> 01:11:51.689
don't become a dealer;
that's the way it is.

01:11:51.689 --> 01:11:55.307
The people who are in this
business are people who can

01:11:55.307 --> 01:11:59.744
tolerate this prospect of ruin.
On the other hand,

01:11:59.744 --> 01:12:02.917
ruin isn't death;
that's another thing you were

01:12:02.917 --> 01:12:05.316
saying.
I can make a living doing this

01:12:05.316 --> 01:12:09.499
for a while and I am taking
money out and that's part of the

01:12:09.499 --> 01:12:12.055
strategy.
Maybe I'm just being too much

01:12:12.055 --> 01:12:15.158
of an academic here.
I live in great comfort in

01:12:15.158 --> 01:12:18.250
academia and these beautiful
surroundings.

01:12:18.250 --> 01:12:21.560
This university has been around
for 300 years;

01:12:21.560 --> 01:12:26.051
I have no worries.
So, you might want to consider

01:12:26.051 --> 01:12:29.979
an academic career instead of a
career in finance.

01:12:29.979 --> 01:12:35.020
I hope to see you again then on
Friday.

01:12:35.020 --> 01:12:38.000
I think we'll have a good time
with Schwarzman.

